<DOC><DOCNO> AP880706-0139 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-88 1238EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-BRF--HungerStrike     07-06 0174</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Hunger Strike,0183</SECOND><HEAD>Conscientious Objectors End Hunger Strike</HEAD><DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two conscientious objectors have endedtheir hunger strike after the government pledged to change the lawon non-combatant military service, their support committee saidWednesday.   The government announced on July 1 that alternative civilianservice had been provided for in a law to be proposed to parliamentthis week.   Mihalis Marangakis, 31, and Thanassis Makris, 23, both jailedGreek Orthodox pacifists, were ``in bad shape'' after the fasting,the committee said.   Makris, a student, has been hospitalized, according to MaryKostidou, the committee secretary. She did not know how much weighthe had lost.   He began fasting May 8 after a military court sentenced him tofive years in prison for resisting military service.   Marangakis, 31, a woodcarver, started his fast May 30 to protestMakris' sentence. Marangakis is serving a 26-month prison term forrefusing to be drafted.   The new bill includes a provision under which the timeconscientious objectors have served in jail will be counted associal service.</TEXT></DOC>